29:34.445 --> 29:36.247
through the other.

29:41.694 --> 29:47.080
When the Secretary of State announced to the world 
that our security line It was Japan, Taiwan,

29:47.785 --> 29:54.395
Philippines, Okinawa, and on around. Eliminated 
Korea. And then what happened? And if you said

29:59.662 --> 30:03.067
that, then we phased out our troops. Now, North 
Koreans look and said, well, they invited us. They

30:07.194 --> 30:12.862
said, this isn't vital to the security of the 
United States. So now's the time to move in. So they

30:15.781 --> 30:17.263
attacked, and what happened? Harry Truman 
managed to declare not an emergency, not a war, but

30:17.323 --> 30:27.634
a police action. And then we found we were in a 
full-blown war with no troops prepared, no

30:27.654 --> 30:34.602
equipment. The units we had in Japan at that time 
not only were understrength and under-equipped,

30:34.622 --> 30:40.789
they weren't even... Some had a phantom, a ghost, 
regiment because division had two regiments

30:46.409 --> 30:52.981
under strength. Air Force wasn't ready at all. 
Neither was the Navy. And all at once we found that

30:58.651 --> 31:01.216
we were in a war. And so we know what happened. We put 
in and we were in a battle and finally got kicked

31:02.638 --> 31:07.607
around all the way down to the perimeter. and 
fought back with all those casualties. Of course,

31:11.099 --> 31:15.603
those casualties didn't seem so large now since we 
had Vietnam all these years. That's another

31:15.623 --> 31:16.524
question. When you were in Korea, did the Gulf of 
Tonkin and then the subsequent buildup in Vietnam

31:16.724 --> 31:29.716
have any impact on your maneuvers, your training, 
your efficiency in Korea? Because there, just

31:30.517 --> 31:35.822
like in Germany, we're supposed to be combat ready 
to fight. It can't even be an alert there because

31:37.220 --> 31:44.729
the DMZ, where we were sitting, we were up to see the 
DMZ. And we had troops actually on the DMZ. 1st

31:47.472 --> 31:51.156
Cavalry Division had troops on the DMZ. We don't 
any longer. We go back where we don't man. And the

31:55.562 --> 32:00.808
Koreans manned on the DMZ since we lost one 
division.

32:02.370 --> 32:02.670
No. We were always on alert, see, and we had 
practice alert, just like we had in Europe. It was

32:10.778 --> 32:19.046
easier there because we didn't have people out 
living with their families in apartments, you

32:10.778 --> 32:19.046
know, 15, 20 miles away. All you had to do was wake 
the people up and get in the vehicles and move to

32:19.066 --> 32:24.310
dispersal area. After that, from 65 to 68, you had 
a, to me, it looks like a very important job in the

32:25.672 --> 32:31.717
Pentagon. Oh, yeah. That

32:34.257 --> 32:43.866
was in the National Military Command Center. As 
Deputy Director of Operations and later Chief of

32:43.886 --> 32:49.571
Far Eastern Division Plans and Policy. Yeah. All 
in the Joint Staff. Thinking about a pressure job

32:52.153 --> 32:55.917
now. That National Military Command Center. 
Because you're actually the duty officer of the

32:58.339 --> 33:01.902
world. and certainly the duty officer of the 
United States, because all of the elements of

33:03.198 --> 33:18.672
government look to this military command post to 
answer questions, because we have the facility to

33:03.198 --> 33:18.672
do that. What happens anywhere in the world? So 
basically what you're doing in the National

33:21.855 --> 33:25.759
Military Command Center is information? Command 
and control of all the armed forces. U.S. and

33:32.155 --> 33:34.318
deployed overseas.

33:37.783 --> 33:44.732
And I'll describe, it's in the Pentagon, in the 
Joint Staff's area. And of course you have to have

33:46.274 --> 33:49.999
special clearance and a special path to get in. 
Because then you don't have this, or sometimes you

33:50.941 --> 34:01.555
have VIPs that they take in, and the Goldwater and a 
few like that come in. But you have a brigadier

34:02.311 --> 34:09.902
general or a flag officer on duty 24 hours a day. 
And, of course, we have Air Force Navy admins in the

34:11.344 --> 34:14.889
Army. And you have an assistant that sits there 
with you. I say sit because it's a big room, almost

34:22.360 --> 34:29.611
as big as a football field, but not quite. It's 
almost an issue. configured almost like that. And

34:34.826 --> 34:37.811
we're up here with all of our telephones. And out on 
the floor, you have representatives of the CIA,

34:39.634 --> 34:56.240
the State Department, Defense Intelligence, 
USIA, and area specialists, which could be manned

34:39.634 --> 34:56.240
by Army, Navy, Air Force. It doesn't make any 
difference. So that every part of the world, you

34:58.370 --> 35:10.921
have an individual who is monitoring on an 
hour-to-hour basis, day-to-day, what the

34:58.370 --> 35:10.921
situation is there, what we have. In the case of the 
Navy, they can answer where all of the ships are.

35:16.526 --> 35:18.628
They monitor all of the ships worldwide. The 
Persian government, any time, they can tell you

35:19.409 --> 35:26.535
what it is.

